{
  "doc_id": "46360",
  "text": "Disruption of the Wnt pathway has been implicated in non-small cell lung cancer. Wnt2 is overexpressed in NSCLC, and inhibition of Wnt2-mediated signaling by siRNA or a monoclonal antibody results in apoptosis of NSCLC cell lines [CITATION_1] . Wnt inhibitory factor (WIF1), a secreted Wnt antagonist, inhibits NSCLC cell line growth in vitro and in vivo, and is also downregulated in NSCLC [CITATION_2] . WIF1 silencing is associated with hypermethylation of its promoter. Methylation-silencing of WIF1 is a common mechanism for aberrant activation of Wnt signaling in lung cancer [CITATION_3] . Disheveled (dvl) proteins are positive mediators of Wnt signaling. Dvl 3 is overexpressed in 75% of freshly microdissected NSCLC tissue specimens [CITATION_4] . Inhibition of dvl1, 2 and 3 resulted in decreased β-catenin, TCF-mediated transcription and inhibition of cell growth in NSCLC cell lines [CITATION_5] . One can speculate that blocking the Wnt signaling pathway may be also an attractive target for therapeutic agents.",
